In the above example, that same ten pounds per week in insurance costs might prevent you from having to shell out countless pounds for emergency breakdown recovery. Inside a worst case scenario in which you don't have the money to pay for this particular service lying around, you will find it difficult to retrieve your vehicle and this may cause you to incur both the costs of vehicle replacement and lack of earnings whilst you make alternative arrangements.

Thankfully for those of us who can't afford to cover the most comprehensive cover, there are some different tiers of breakdown insurance available and also the cheapest is usually reasonably priced. Whilst these insurance plans will offer no-frills services, they'll be greatly better than having no cover whatsoever in case of a failure. It is worth bearing in mind that the cheapest plans will probably make you exposed to lack of earnings and could result in additional costs - often diets allows the recovery team to deposit your vehicle in a nearby garage of the choice. These garages will rarely provide you with the best affordability or the best possible service because it is not in their best interest to spend the required money to do so. After all, you are unlikely revisit exactly the same motorway garage in the near future so that they won't take advantage of your positive connection with their work.

Deciding on the best breakdown insurance policy for you can be challenging, and as with any insurance contract you ought to be careful to read all the relevant terms and conditions before you sign the contract.

Remember that insurance should not be seen as a cost but being an purchase of your security and peace of mind: the last thing you would like is to be stranded by the roadside for an indefinite length of time.